result.execSummary:
The defendant Cassie S Colby was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Cassie S Colby is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Cassie S Colby was found guilty of Burglary-Armed w/ Dangerous Weapon [Modifiers: Repeater], a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(2)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

438 days credit.
Pursuant to Motion Hearing on 04/27/2016, Court orders defendant is eligible for CIP and Substance Abuse Program.  Also, upon release from Taycheedah Correctional Institution, defendant must be placed for at least 6 months in a community-based transitional rehabilitative housing facility and/or a community-based AODA treatment facility upon release unless the Department of Corrections sends a written explanation to the Court why the defendant is not being placed.
Concurrent with: with all other sentences

superMiscConds.notes: Plus supervision fees.    If discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due. All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt.  $250 represents the mandatory DNA Surcharge.    $10 represents the mandatory statutory surcharge for 943 property crimes.
Any assessment and counseling as required and follow through and complete all required treatment.

Not to possess or consume any illegal drugs.    Not to possess or consume any alcohol.  Not to possess any drug paraphernalia.  Not to go on any premises where primary purpose is the sale of alcohol.  No contact with:  Morgan J Tiry or his daughter, MFI, or his residence without written permission from the Probation Agent and victim; Heath Jassoy or his residence without written permission from Probation Agent and victim.    Not to possess any firearms.
Submit a DNA sample.  Defendant to take all prescribed medications.  Defendant to maintain absolute sobriety.
